55
00:03:10,400 --> 00:03:15,655
I want ice cream.
What flavor is it? What flavor is it?

56
00:03:19,325 --> 00:03:21,452
(POLICE SIREN BLARING)

57
00:03:24,038 --> 00:03:25,290
(CAT MEWS)

58
00:03:34,507 --> 00:03:36,467
- BRUCE: Hey.
- Hey yourself.

59
00:03:43,516 --> 00:03:45,184
What? You asked me for it.

60
00:03:45,810 --> 00:03:47,770
- I know.
- If you don't want it--

61
00:03:47,937 --> 00:03:48,938
I want it.

62
00:03:49,814 --> 00:03:51,149
You look scared.

63
00:03:53,484 --> 00:03:54,861
I'm not.

64
00:04:00,033 --> 00:04:02,911
- Is it loaded?
- Ain't no point in an unloaded gun.

65
00:04:03,703 --> 00:04:06,623
Guns aren't for show, Bruce,
and they're not for protection.

66
00:04:08,166 --> 00:04:09,626
They're only for one thing.

67
00:04:14,088 --> 00:04:15,423
Of course.

68
00:04:15,965 --> 00:04:17,425
They're only for one thing.

69
00:04:28,561 --> 00:04:29,562
(CLEARS THROAT)

70
00:04:31,564 --> 00:04:34,609
- Lee, good morning.
- Hey.

71
00:04:35,693 --> 00:04:37,487
Look, what we talked about after Arkham--

72
00:04:37,654 --> 00:04:40,782
It's not why I'm here.
I wanted you to take a look at these.

73
00:04:40,949 --> 00:04:43,159
It's Kristen Kringle's final paychecks.

74
00:04:43,326 --> 00:04:45,411
Her paychecks? How'd you get these?

75
00:04:45,954 --> 00:04:49,207
I went to human resources to get
her new address and they gave them to me.

76
00:04:49,582 --> 00:04:52,210
She never picked them up.
They don't know where she is.

77
00:04:52,377 --> 00:04:54,712
She never cashed them,
never left a forwarding address.

78
00:04:55,254 --> 00:04:56,714
That's odd.

79
00:04:57,340 --> 00:04:59,467
Well, Dougherty has money.
Maybe they're traveling.

80
00:05:00,677 --> 00:05:03,972
I don't like it.
She said that Dougherty hurt her before.

81
00:05:04,138 --> 00:05:07,225
Really? Have you talked to Ed about it?

82
00:05:07,392 --> 00:05:09,018
- No.
- Maybe he's heard from her.

83
00:05:09,185 --> 00:05:11,396
I didn't feel like
it was right to worry him.

84
00:05:11,813 --> 00:05:13,398
I just want to know that she's all right.

85
00:05:15,316 --> 00:05:16,401
I can take it to Missing Persons.

86
00:05:16,901 --> 00:05:18,403
No, no, that's all right.
I'll look into it.

87
00:05:20,238 --> 00:05:21,781
Let you know what I find.

88
00:05:22,991 --> 00:05:24,075
Thank you.

89
00:05:24,242 --> 00:05:25,243
Yeah.

90
00:05:41,801 --> 00:05:44,887
Ah, Master Bruce. You ready?

91
00:05:46,055 --> 00:05:47,056
Yes.

92
00:05:48,057 --> 00:05:49,308
I'm gonna need more than that.

93
00:05:49,517 --> 00:05:51,769
<i>We're on the hunt
of an extremely dangerous man.</i>

94
00:05:51,936 --> 00:05:53,521
<i>This is life and death stuff.</i>

95
00:05:53,688 --> 00:05:57,483
I need you to tell me that you are sure.
Now, are you sure?

96
00:06:03,281 --> 00:06:05,450
Yes, Alfred. I'm sure.

97
00:06:05,700 --> 00:06:08,745
Right. And when we're on the street,

98
00:06:08,911 --> 00:06:11,456
you follow my every lead,
no faffing about, is that understood?

99
00:06:12,248 --> 00:06:14,292
- Yes.
- Good lad.

100
00:06:15,960 --> 00:06:18,337
Our quarry is an east side boy.

101
00:06:18,504 --> 00:06:21,299
This misspent youth,
Patrick Matches Malone,

102
00:06:21,466 --> 00:06:24,135
was arrested several times
with a geezer called Cupcake.

103
00:06:24,802 --> 00:06:26,596
I suspect there's irony at play there.

104
00:06:27,263 --> 00:06:29,307
They're partners in crime
until Matches' testimony

105
00:06:29,474 --> 00:06:33,227
put Mr. Cupcake
in the Blackgate Pen for 10.

106
00:06:33,978 --> 00:06:35,354
Says here that Cupcake is out now,

107
00:06:35,521 --> 00:06:39,108
and he runs this strong-arm
little firm called "The Mutants."

108
00:06:41,152 --> 00:06:43,279
So, I guess we have to start there then.

109
00:06:43,529 --> 00:06:45,031
MOHAWK: <i>Solomon.</i>
CHICKEN: <i>Grundy.</i>

110
00:06:45,281 --> 00:06:46,491
(BOTH GRUNTING)

111
00:06:46,741 --> 00:06:48,409
- Solomon.
- Grundy.

112
00:06:49,702 --> 00:06:51,746
(CROWD CHEERING)

113
00:06:52,038 --> 00:06:53,206
Remember. Let me do the talking.

114
00:06:53,372 --> 00:06:55,166
I know how to handle this type, all right?

115
00:06:55,333 --> 00:06:58,628
Good afternoon, ladies and gentlemen.
Hope we find you well.

116
00:07:00,463 --> 00:07:04,842
We're hoping to have a little chat
with a gentleman called Cupcake.

117
00:07:05,760 --> 00:07:08,763
You found me, sweetheart. What's up?

118
00:07:09,180 --> 00:07:11,599
Mr. Cupcake, pleasure to meet you.

119
00:07:12,391 --> 00:07:14,268
My name's Alfred Pennyworth.

120
00:07:14,435 --> 00:07:17,939
Now, we're on the hunt for a guy
called Matches Malone.

121
00:07:18,106 --> 00:07:19,816
Now, we know
he stitched you up a few years ago,

122
00:07:19,982 --> 00:07:23,194
so I'm sure you wouldn't mind returning
the favor, if you know what I mean.

123
00:07:24,112 --> 00:07:25,404
- Who's your friend?
- Never mind who he is...

124
00:07:25,571 --> 00:07:28,449
- I'm Bruce Wayne.
- Boy billionaire Bruce Wayne?

125
00:07:30,326 --> 00:07:31,494
That one.

126
00:07:31,702 --> 00:07:33,412
I'm willing to pay you a lot of money

127
00:07:33,579 --> 00:07:35,039
if you can tell us where to find Malone.

128
00:07:35,206 --> 00:07:36,707
Oh, really? Why?

129
00:07:37,333 --> 00:07:39,544
- Master Bruce, please let me talk--
- I think he killed my parents.

130
00:07:39,877 --> 00:07:42,171
- Oh, that's a good answer.
- (CROWD LAUGHING)

131
00:07:42,380 --> 00:07:43,714
How much money?

132
00:07:44,590 --> 00:07:47,218
- How much will make you talk?
- $1 million.

133
00:07:47,385 --> 00:07:49,262
- MAN: Hell yeah.
- (INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

134
00:07:49,470 --> 00:07:51,597
- That's too much.
- (SCOFFS) The boy is cheap.

135
00:07:52,682 --> 00:07:54,725
Mr. Cupcake, if I may be so bold as to--

136
00:07:54,892 --> 00:07:57,812
- Yo, I'm talking to the shot caller.
- MAN: That's right.

137
00:07:57,979 --> 00:07:59,397
Tell you what, son, I'll make you a deal.

138
00:07:59,564 --> 00:08:02,567
Give me $50,000. You won't get Matches,

139
00:08:02,733 --> 00:08:04,902
but you get to leave here
with your fingers and toes.

140
00:08:05,069 --> 00:08:06,070
(LAUGHS)

141
00:08:06,362 --> 00:08:07,488
Steady on, pal.

142
00:08:07,655 --> 00:08:09,574
I'm just messing with you.

143
00:08:09,740 --> 00:08:12,410
I wouldn't hurt the little boy.
I like little boys.

144
00:08:12,577 --> 00:08:15,872
You on the other hand,
I'm not sure about you.

145
00:08:16,038 --> 00:08:18,749
Tell you what, I'll give you
that rat Matches for 50 grand.

146
00:08:18,916 --> 00:08:23,087
But first, you must fight me. (CHUCKLES)

147
00:08:23,588 --> 00:08:25,798
- I beg your-- Excuse me?
- Fight me, baby.

148
00:08:25,965 --> 00:08:29,427
No, you see, I'm not really a...
I'm not really a fighter.

149
00:08:29,594 --> 00:08:33,598
Oh, shh. I saw you step up just now.
"Steady on, pal." (CHUCKLES)

150
00:08:33,764 --> 00:08:35,433
Mr. Cupcake, I really can't foresee

151
00:08:35,600 --> 00:08:38,519
anything positive
coming out of this altercation.

152
00:08:38,686 --> 00:08:41,814
You're in my house.
Fight is what we do here.

153
00:08:41,981 --> 00:08:43,441
- Yeah.
- That's right.

154
00:08:43,649 --> 00:08:46,652
I'll pay you $100,000
for the name and no fighting.

155
00:08:46,819 --> 00:08:50,281
I'm not about money, little boy.
I'm about respect.

156
00:08:50,573 --> 00:08:52,450
No fight, no deal.

157
00:08:52,617 --> 00:08:55,786
No Matches. No exit.

158
00:08:58,623 --> 00:09:03,002
All right, well, I suppose, you know,
Mr. Cupcake, if you put it like that...

159
00:09:10,384 --> 00:09:12,511
If you wouldn't mind, sir.

160
00:09:12,678 --> 00:09:13,679
Will you be all right?

161
00:09:13,971 --> 00:09:15,806
We'll have to wait and see, won't we?

162
00:09:15,973 --> 00:09:17,642
Are you acting like this is my fault?

163
00:09:18,517 --> 00:09:20,770
- It's not for me to say, is it, sir?
- How is it my fault?

164
00:09:20,937 --> 00:09:22,980
I told you to let me do the talking,
did I not?

165
00:09:23,147 --> 00:09:26,484
And did you do the talking? Yes. I think
you'll find yes, you did do the talking.

166
00:09:26,651 --> 00:09:29,362
To be fair, I think the result
would have been similar in any case.

167
00:09:29,528 --> 00:09:33,157
If, Master Bruce, we are lucky enough
to walk away from this alive,

168
00:09:33,950 --> 00:09:37,787
let this be a lesson to you.
And another thing, pick your battles.

169
00:09:38,079 --> 00:09:39,830
Don't let them pick you.

170
00:09:40,289 --> 00:09:45,836
Right. On your honor, I win, we walk.

171
00:09:46,045 --> 00:09:50,174
Sure thing, mister. On my honor.
They'll understand.

172
00:09:50,341 --> 00:09:54,053
But the fight doesn't stop till somebody
says "uncle," or goes to sleep.

173
00:09:54,220 --> 00:09:55,763
Now, get it on.

174
00:09:56,806 --> 00:09:59,475
The other thing, of course, Master Bruce,
to remember,

175
00:09:59,850 --> 00:10:02,103
is that timing is everything.

176
00:10:02,353 --> 00:10:03,854
- (GRUNTS)
- (CROWD EXCLAIMS)

177
00:10:04,063 --> 00:10:05,648
(BOTH GRUNTING)

178
00:10:15,408 --> 00:10:19,370
See, there's other factors at play here,
Master Bruce. There's footwork. Leverage--

179
00:10:19,537 --> 00:10:21,038
Stop talking.

180
00:10:24,500 --> 00:10:26,085
(CROWD CHEERING)

181
00:10:29,422 --> 00:10:31,173
What? What, you want some?

182
00:10:31,507 --> 00:10:33,259
(CUPCAKE GRUNTING)

183
00:10:33,801 --> 00:10:35,303
(CROWD EXCLAIMING)

184
00:10:38,264 --> 00:10:39,890
(CUPCAKE GRUNTING)

185
00:10:40,182 --> 00:10:41,350
Alfred!

186
00:10:41,559 --> 00:10:43,227
(CROWD CHEERING)

187
00:10:46,689 --> 00:10:48,065
Uncle! Uncle!

188
00:10:48,232 --> 00:10:51,819
No! He's slowing.

189
00:11:02,246 --> 00:11:06,083
See, Master Bruce.
Big muscles require lots of blood.

190
00:11:06,334 --> 00:11:07,793
(CUPCAKE GROANING)

191
00:11:08,085 --> 00:11:10,421
Strength costs wind.

192
00:11:10,713 --> 00:11:13,632
Now, if you gotta beat a big man,
all you have to do

193
00:11:14,342 --> 00:11:15,676
is outlast him.

194
00:11:16,218 --> 00:11:17,803
No. No.

195
00:11:18,763 --> 00:11:19,847
Uncle, uncle.

196
00:11:20,431 --> 00:11:22,767
I'm calling it, the butler wins.

197
00:11:25,019 --> 00:11:28,606
- Are you okay?
- I'm absolutely flipping peachy, mate.

198
00:11:31,692 --> 00:11:33,652
You're a tough old cat.

199
00:11:34,195 --> 00:11:37,531
Not too shabby yourself, Mr. Cupcake.
Matches?

200
00:11:37,907 --> 00:11:40,951
- (PANTING) Fifty grand.
- Will, will a check be all right?

201
00:11:41,327 --> 00:11:43,120
(CROWD LAUGHING)

202
00:11:43,537 --> 00:11:46,957
Yeah, yeah, sure, a check will be fine.
Make it out to cash.

203
00:11:47,124 --> 00:11:50,169
Go see Jeri down at Celestial Garden,
it's on the east side.

204
00:11:51,170 --> 00:11:53,047
She'll know where to find Matches.

205
00:11:53,214 --> 00:11:56,008
Pleasure doing business with you,
Mr. Cupcake.

206
00:12:02,848 --> 00:12:04,517
How do you feel?

207
00:12:05,017 --> 00:12:07,144
A couple of hours kip,
and I'll come up lovely.

208
00:12:08,312 --> 00:12:09,522
Good.

209
00:12:10,022 --> 00:12:11,315
You stay here.

210
00:12:12,191 --> 00:12:16,779
You ain't going nowhere
till I'm up and about, all right?

211
00:12:19,031 --> 00:12:20,366
Yes. I hear you.

212
00:12:21,951 --> 00:12:23,953
Promise me, Master B.

213
00:12:25,204 --> 00:12:26,247
Say again?

214
00:12:27,248 --> 00:12:28,999
(INAUDIBLE)

215
00:12:39,510 --> 00:12:40,719
Sorry.

216
00:12:48,686 --> 00:12:50,229
- Blood.
- Life.

217
00:12:51,063 --> 00:12:52,606
Throat.

218
00:12:52,773 --> 00:12:53,858
Song.

219
00:12:54,024 --> 00:12:55,693
- Cat.
- Kitten.

220
00:12:55,860 --> 00:12:57,945
- Mother.
- Hug.

221
00:12:58,195 --> 00:12:59,905
- Crime.
- Punishment.

222
00:13:00,072 --> 00:13:01,365
Revenge.

223
00:13:02,032 --> 00:13:03,117
Remorse.

224
00:13:03,284 --> 00:13:05,828
Ah, remorse. Let's talk about that.

225
00:13:07,079 --> 00:13:09,123
I feel it. A lot.

226
00:13:09,290 --> 00:13:13,878
Remorse is progress. Remorse is huge.

227
00:13:14,670 --> 00:13:16,213
Is it?

228
00:13:16,380 --> 00:13:21,177
I feel terrible about stuff. (SNIFFLES)
I was so mean to people.

229
00:13:21,343 --> 00:13:25,097
Remorse is a healthy and natural response
of the human condition.

230
00:13:25,264 --> 00:13:29,768
It is a good sign. It is a normal sign.

231
00:13:30,561 --> 00:13:32,313
I want to be normal.

232
00:13:32,897 --> 00:13:34,356
I want to be good.

233
00:13:36,066 --> 00:13:37,401
(GROANS SOFTLY)

234
00:13:38,068 --> 00:13:39,820
You must think I'm lying to you.

235
00:13:40,112 --> 00:13:41,447
Oh, no. (CHUCKLES)

236
00:13:43,324 --> 00:13:45,409
I can tell when someone's lying to me.

237
00:13:46,327 --> 00:13:50,706
Oswald, you are making
a magnificent transformation.

238
00:13:50,873 --> 00:13:52,875
Your real self is emerging.

239
00:13:53,083 --> 00:13:55,794
<i>A kind, decent, young man.</i>

240
00:13:56,253 --> 00:13:59,256
Just a few more therapy sessions
and you'll be right as rain.

241
00:14:02,384 --> 00:14:03,802
More therapy?

242
00:14:03,969 --> 00:14:05,429
Oh, just a little.

243
00:14:05,596 --> 00:14:08,265
I know there's a discomfort factor,

244
00:14:08,432 --> 00:14:13,437
but after all,
it is making you better, yes?

245
00:14:14,438 --> 00:14:17,691
Oh, you do want to get better,

246
00:14:19,401 --> 00:14:20,486
don't you?

247
00:14:22,780 --> 00:14:24,490
Yes, Professor Strange.

248
00:14:25,074 --> 00:14:28,327
(CHUCKLES) Oswald, please. Call me Hugo.

249
00:14:30,412 --> 00:14:31,872
Yes, Hugo.

250
00:14:36,794 --> 00:14:38,128
(SIGHS)

251
00:14:39,129 --> 00:14:40,130
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

252
00:14:40,506 --> 00:14:41,674
Hey, Ed. You busy?

253
00:14:41,840 --> 00:14:44,134
I'm studying the decomp rate
of various colors of ink

254
00:14:44,301 --> 00:14:46,971
to see if we can use tattoos
to help determine time of death.

255
00:14:47,179 --> 00:14:49,306
Hmm, is that a yes or a no?

256
00:14:50,641 --> 00:14:52,810
Please come in. How can I help you?

257
00:14:54,812 --> 00:14:58,315
I was wondering if you'd heard
from Kristen Kringle lately.

258
00:15:00,985 --> 00:15:04,405
I'm strong as a rock,
but a word can destroy me. What am I?

259
00:15:06,949 --> 00:15:08,534
Silence. I've heard nothing.

260
00:15:09,535 --> 00:15:11,203
Well, I don't want to alarm you,

261
00:15:11,370 --> 00:15:13,831
but we can't seem to locate her.

262
00:15:14,373 --> 00:15:16,834
She hasn't cashed her last few paychecks.

263
00:15:17,334 --> 00:15:19,336
Oh, my Lord. Do you...

264
00:15:20,212 --> 00:15:22,339
Do you think
that something bad has happened?

265
00:15:22,631 --> 00:15:24,883
No. No, no. We're not there yet, anyway.

266
00:15:25,050 --> 00:15:26,218
We? Who is we?

267
00:15:26,385 --> 00:15:29,138
Oh, just me and my curiosity.

268
00:15:29,305 --> 00:15:32,141
I don't know Tom Dougherty well.
What is he like?

269
00:15:32,516 --> 00:15:35,185
(INHALES DEEPLY)
What is Tom Dougherty like?

270
00:15:35,769 --> 00:15:37,438
(SIGHS) Rotten.

271
00:15:37,688 --> 00:15:39,773
Hmm, that's what I'd heard.

272
00:15:39,940 --> 00:15:43,736
And Kringle told you herself
that she was moving south with Dougherty?

273
00:15:43,902 --> 00:15:46,113
Not in person. She left a note.

274
00:15:46,280 --> 00:15:47,865
Can I take a look at it?

275
00:15:48,866 --> 00:15:51,243
I didn't really think of it as a keepsake.

276
00:15:53,829 --> 00:15:55,205
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

277
00:15:55,497 --> 00:15:58,959
Right. Yeah, excuse me.

278
00:16:01,170 --> 00:16:02,463
<i>Yeah.</i>

279
00:16:03,714 --> 00:16:07,843
(SIGHS) Again? Yeah, okay. I'm on my way.

280
00:16:09,595 --> 00:16:12,473
- (DOOR CLOSES)
- So, that's the game, is it, Jimbo?

281
00:16:13,557 --> 00:16:16,018
Gonna try to outsmart me?

282
00:16:16,185 --> 00:16:18,228
Play me for a fool?

283
00:16:20,022 --> 00:16:21,523
I don't think so.

284
00:16:25,736 --> 00:16:27,071
Well, that took you long enough.

285
00:16:27,237 --> 00:16:29,448
For a butler,
you sure do get beat up a lot.

286
00:16:29,615 --> 00:16:30,658
What happened?

287
00:16:30,824 --> 00:16:32,076
We got his name, Jim.

288
00:16:32,242 --> 00:16:34,453
The name of the man
that killed Bruce's parents.

289
00:16:35,162 --> 00:16:36,413
Matches Malone.

290
00:16:36,872 --> 00:16:38,582
BULLOCK: Dude, we're the cops.

291
00:16:38,749 --> 00:16:41,669
Thank you for sharing this with us.
When were you gonna tell us?

292
00:16:41,835 --> 00:16:43,962
I haven't got time to explain now.

293
00:16:44,129 --> 00:16:45,881
We got a good solid lead
from the same place

294
00:16:46,048 --> 00:16:47,841
that I got seven bells knocked out of me.

295
00:16:48,008 --> 00:16:49,301
Now Bruce, he won't answer his phone.

296
00:16:49,468 --> 00:16:52,429
So, my guess is
he's gone after this Malone.

297
00:16:53,055 --> 00:16:54,098
Solo.

298
00:16:54,264 --> 00:16:56,308
Going after him? To do what exactly?

299
00:16:56,475 --> 00:16:57,768
What can he do? He's a kid.

300
00:16:57,935 --> 00:16:59,269
ALFRED: <i>Only reason to go alone.</i>

301
00:16:59,812 --> 00:17:01,230
He's gonna kill the man.

302
00:17:02,648 --> 00:17:05,401
<i>I mean, I, I told him not to.
I said you're too young for killing.</i>

303
00:17:05,567 --> 00:17:06,735
Said I'd do it for him.

304
00:17:06,902 --> 00:17:10,239
Again. We're the cops.
Do not tell us stuff like this.

305
00:17:10,406 --> 00:17:12,950
You've got to understand. Both of ya.

306
00:17:15,369 --> 00:17:16,495
This is not a game.

307
00:17:17,454 --> 00:17:18,622
I understand.

308
00:17:19,498 --> 00:17:20,874
Tell me where he is.

309
00:17:23,460 --> 00:17:24,712
Hey, cowboy.

310
00:17:26,296 --> 00:17:27,756
Yes, sir?

311
00:17:27,965 --> 00:17:29,216
(CHUCKLES)

312
00:17:29,466 --> 00:17:30,634
Have fun.

313
00:17:33,512 --> 00:17:35,472
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

314
00:17:35,764 --> 00:17:37,641
(PEOPLE CHEERING INDISTINCTLY)

315
00:17:44,982 --> 00:17:47,234
(JERI SINGING THE DAMNED SONG
"NEW ROSE")

316
00:18:12,801 --> 00:18:14,678
(CROWD CHEERING)

317
00:18:16,847 --> 00:18:20,142
Ha! Hello, Bruce. What took you so long?

318
00:18:22,227 --> 00:18:23,479
I'm looking for Jeri.

319
00:18:23,645 --> 00:18:24,980
Yeah, you are.

320
00:18:26,231 --> 00:18:27,691
Follow me.

321
00:18:42,748 --> 00:18:44,708
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

322
00:18:45,793 --> 00:18:47,127
Come.

323
00:18:58,305 --> 00:18:59,807
(MAN COUGHS)

324
00:19:02,351 --> 00:19:03,769
(GIRL CHUCKLES)

325
00:19:15,906 --> 00:19:18,700
(SIGHS) Come.

326
00:19:21,036 --> 00:19:22,412
Take a pew.

327
00:19:23,580 --> 00:19:25,916
Iced tea? Soda? (CHUCKLES)

328
00:19:26,500 --> 00:19:28,252
- No, thank you.
- (DOOR CLOSES)

329
00:19:29,795 --> 00:19:30,796
You like the show?

330
00:19:31,380 --> 00:19:32,673
I liked it.

331
00:19:32,840 --> 00:19:34,758
- Are you Jeri?
- (CHUCKLES)

332
00:19:34,925 --> 00:19:36,426
Some people call me that.

333
00:19:44,977 --> 00:19:47,062
What? What can I do for you?

334
00:19:47,229 --> 00:19:48,230
Oh...

335
00:19:49,273 --> 00:19:52,025
Sorry. You know my name,
so Cupcake called you.

336
00:19:52,192 --> 00:19:54,444
I assumed you already know why I'm here.

337
00:19:54,611 --> 00:19:56,947
I just want you to say it.

338
00:19:57,948 --> 00:19:59,700
I'm looking for Matches Malone.

339
00:20:00,284 --> 00:20:01,326
Why?

340
00:20:02,578 --> 00:20:03,954
He killed my parents.

341
00:20:05,789 --> 00:20:07,457
What you gonna do if you find him?

342
00:20:08,667 --> 00:20:10,127
Ask him some questions.

343
00:20:14,131 --> 00:20:15,132
Kill him.

344
00:20:15,465 --> 00:20:17,050
(LAUGHING)

345
00:20:18,135 --> 00:20:19,636
Okay, I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

346
00:20:20,095 --> 00:20:23,473
Killing people isn't, you know, that easy.

347
00:20:23,640 --> 00:20:27,269
Hey, maybe you've killed people before.
You've killed people before, blood?

348
00:20:27,477 --> 00:20:28,812
No.

349
00:20:30,522 --> 00:20:32,316
But no one's killed my parents before.

350
00:20:35,152 --> 00:20:38,071
Well, Matches has killed dozens of people.

351
00:20:39,698 --> 00:20:42,159
<i>Men, women, children.</i>

352
00:20:43,869 --> 00:20:45,495
He's a professional.

353
00:20:46,455 --> 00:20:49,082
And what exactly are you?

354
00:20:51,877 --> 00:20:53,003
Do you know where he is?

355
00:20:53,211 --> 00:20:55,339
Of course I know where he is,
he's a friend of mine.

356
00:20:55,505 --> 00:20:58,508
You gonna give me a good reason
to tell you where he is?

357
00:21:00,177 --> 00:21:02,596
- Justice.
- (LAUGHS) Please.

358
00:21:03,388 --> 00:21:05,515
- Money.
- No. I don't care about money.

359
00:21:05,682 --> 00:21:07,142
Try something else.

360
00:21:10,228 --> 00:21:11,813
I have a gun.

361
00:21:12,689 --> 00:21:14,149
That's a good reason.

362
00:21:15,901 --> 00:21:17,110
Please.

363
00:21:18,028 --> 00:21:19,112
Tell me where he is.

364
00:21:20,364 --> 00:21:23,367
Come on, kid,
you ain't even pointing at me!

365
00:21:24,785 --> 00:21:26,244
(CHUCKLING)

366
00:21:27,371 --> 00:21:29,164
What is your problem?

367
00:21:30,207 --> 00:21:32,042
I've been told it's unwise
to point a gun at someone

368
00:21:32,209 --> 00:21:33,752
if you're not ready to shoot them.

369
00:21:34,002 --> 00:21:35,045
And I'm not.

370
00:21:36,046 --> 00:21:37,381
Very wise young man.

371
00:21:46,598 --> 00:21:47,766
Thank you, Jeri.

372
00:21:49,017 --> 00:21:53,397
It's been interesting talking to you.

373
00:21:58,276 --> 00:22:02,739
Matches lives in that big building
on Grand Street, between 9th and 10th.

374
00:22:03,865 --> 00:22:05,242
Apartment 9B.

375
00:22:09,079 --> 00:22:10,664
Why did you tell me that?

376
00:22:13,458 --> 00:22:14,918
I thought he was your friend.

377
00:22:15,085 --> 00:22:16,086
He is.

378
00:22:17,045 --> 00:22:18,338
Well, he was.

379
00:22:20,215 --> 00:22:22,467
Matches is gonna be happy to see you.

380
00:22:23,093 --> 00:22:26,179
<i>You, my boy,
are the childish hand of fate.</i>

381
00:22:27,597 --> 00:22:30,058
Well, that makes me God,
in a way, doesn't it?

382
00:22:31,518 --> 00:22:32,686
(CHUCKLES)

383
00:22:34,438 --> 00:22:36,773
And who doesn't like to play God?

384
00:22:50,037 --> 00:22:52,122
(CROWD TALKING INDISTINCTLY)

385
00:23:03,216 --> 00:23:04,301
Bruce.

386
00:23:06,261 --> 00:23:07,637
Bruce! Hey.

387
00:23:09,139 --> 00:23:10,182
Please let me go.

388
00:23:10,474 --> 00:23:12,809
Bruce, listen to me.
I know what you're doing.

389
00:23:12,976 --> 00:23:14,644
Alfred told me everything.

390
00:23:15,312 --> 00:23:16,438
He shouldn't have done that.

391
00:23:16,980 --> 00:23:18,315
I understand how you feel.

392
00:23:18,482 --> 00:23:19,566
No, you don't.

393
00:23:19,775 --> 00:23:22,486
No, you're right, I don't.
And it doesn't matter.

394
00:23:22,694 --> 00:23:24,613
This is as far as you go.

395
00:23:24,780 --> 00:23:25,864
You're gonna take over from here, are you?

396
00:23:26,031 --> 00:23:27,199
Yes, I am.

397
00:23:27,532 --> 00:23:29,659
I'm sorry, Detective Gordon,
that doesn't reassure me.

398
00:23:29,826 --> 00:23:32,037
Bruce, I can't let you do this.

399
00:23:33,163 --> 00:23:36,208
GCPD. One, two, three, four...

400
00:23:36,541 --> 00:23:38,502
- (LOUD MUSIC PLAYING)
- (CROWD CHEERING)

401
00:23:42,005 --> 00:23:43,006
Hey!

402
00:24:02,818 --> 00:24:04,694
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

403
00:25:05,130 --> 00:25:06,590
(DOOR OPENS)

404
00:25:13,513 --> 00:25:15,015
(STUTTERS) Matches Malone?

405
00:25:15,932 --> 00:25:16,933
Mmm-hmm.

406
00:25:22,939 --> 00:25:24,274
I want to hire you.

407
00:25:24,482 --> 00:25:25,775
(CHUCKLES)

408
00:25:26,109 --> 00:25:27,819
Kids now.

409
00:25:33,116 --> 00:25:34,534
So you want to hire me?

410
00:25:35,410 --> 00:25:36,661
I want someone to die.

411
00:25:37,579 --> 00:25:38,830
Wait a while. They will.

412
00:25:39,623 --> 00:25:40,957
I don't wanna wait.

413
00:25:41,750 --> 00:25:43,793
You're kind of young
to be putting out contracts.

414
00:25:43,960 --> 00:25:45,212
I'm old enough.

415
00:25:48,965 --> 00:25:50,508
Are you a proficient killer?

416
00:25:51,259 --> 00:25:52,761
I thought you wanted to hire me.

417
00:25:52,928 --> 00:25:55,305
You didn't say nothing
about a job interview.

418
00:25:56,473 --> 00:25:57,933
I have to be sure
I'm getting the right man.

419
00:25:58,099 --> 00:25:59,935
Don't you know a killer when you see one?

420
00:26:00,101 --> 00:26:01,519
Actually, you look very ordinary.

421
00:26:03,146 --> 00:26:04,689
Have you killed a lot of people?

422
00:26:05,148 --> 00:26:07,651
I've killed all kind of folks

423
00:26:07,817 --> 00:26:09,778
just about every way you can.

424
00:26:10,654 --> 00:26:13,740
Rich, poor, guilty, innocent.

425
00:26:14,324 --> 00:26:16,743
By hand, by blade, by gun.

426
00:26:18,203 --> 00:26:21,998
Burn just one guy to death, they call you
Matches the rest of your days.

427
00:26:22,916 --> 00:26:24,501
Life's funny, isn't it?

428
00:26:28,380 --> 00:26:29,506
Cat got your tongue?

429
00:26:32,259 --> 00:26:34,177
What's the matter, kid? You sick?

430
00:26:36,137 --> 00:26:38,974
Sorry, I'm fine.

431
00:26:39,140 --> 00:26:40,809
Nervous is all.

432
00:26:43,645 --> 00:26:45,605
You seem to be the right man.

433
00:26:46,856 --> 00:26:49,359
Damn right, I am. (SNIFFLES)

434
00:26:53,196 --> 00:26:54,531
Where is Bruce Wayne?

435
00:26:54,698 --> 00:26:56,533
You are so angry.

436
00:26:56,700 --> 00:26:58,785
I'm sensing a personal relationship.

437
00:26:58,952 --> 00:27:01,496
Maybe like a surrogate father
type of thing.

438
00:27:01,663 --> 00:27:03,832
- Where is he?
- He is...

439
00:27:04,207 --> 00:27:05,625
He's a really good kid.

440
00:27:06,376 --> 00:27:08,545
He's got steel in him.

441
00:27:08,712 --> 00:27:10,588
He's gonna grow up
and be a strong man one day.

442
00:27:10,755 --> 00:27:12,382
Well, if he lives long enough.

443
00:27:13,049 --> 00:27:16,594
This is gonna go a lot better for you
if you don't make me angry.

444
00:27:17,220 --> 00:27:21,016
Angry is your natural state, isn't it?
You are the infamous Jim Gordon.

445
00:27:21,725 --> 00:27:23,226
Everybody knows about your temper.

446
00:27:23,393 --> 00:27:26,563
This isn't about me.
There's a kid out there in danger.

447
00:27:26,730 --> 00:27:29,190
Oh, there's lots of kids
out there in danger.

448
00:27:30,358 --> 00:27:34,404
Why does this poor, little, rich boy
got your special attention?

449
00:27:35,071 --> 00:27:36,239
You're trying to make me angry.

450
00:27:38,325 --> 00:27:39,993
Do you want me to hurt you?

451
00:27:41,202 --> 00:27:43,371
Could you? I got nowhere else to be.

452
00:27:43,538 --> 00:27:44,706
No.

453
00:27:45,415 --> 00:27:47,625
Tell me where you sent Bruce Wayne. Now.

454
00:27:47,792 --> 00:27:50,879
You are a lot less fun than advertised.

455
00:27:53,340 --> 00:27:54,716
What time is it?

456
00:27:55,842 --> 00:27:57,302
<i>What time is it?</i>

457
00:27:58,720 --> 00:28:00,430
Yep, he should be there by now.

458
00:28:00,972 --> 00:28:04,017
So you could get there
just in time for the cleanup.

459
00:28:06,269 --> 00:28:08,396
(MAN TALKING INDISTINCTLY OVER RADIO)

460
00:28:11,232 --> 00:28:15,362
Price starts at 10 grand or so
for a simple hit on an adult male vic,

461
00:28:15,528 --> 00:28:18,782
then there's a sliding scale
depending on how hard the job is.

462
00:28:19,532 --> 00:28:22,660
I charge double for women,
and triple for kids.

463
00:28:23,161 --> 00:28:25,955
No babies. I won't kill babies.

464
00:28:27,499 --> 00:28:28,833
Ten grand.

465
00:28:30,085 --> 00:28:31,294
That's cheap.

466
00:28:31,961 --> 00:28:33,338
Low overhead.

467
00:28:34,798 --> 00:28:36,216
Who do you want dead, son?

468
00:28:41,763 --> 00:28:43,890
You really don't remember me, do you?

469
00:28:44,516 --> 00:28:46,142
Remember you?

470
00:28:46,851 --> 00:28:49,646
No. We've met before?

471
00:28:51,314 --> 00:28:53,983
Yes, we've met before.

472
00:29:00,698 --> 00:29:02,409
You killed my parents.

473
00:29:03,701 --> 00:29:04,869
Oh...

474
00:29:14,170 --> 00:29:15,755
Keep your hands where I can see them.

475
00:29:17,841 --> 00:29:19,717
Relax, kid. I won't jump you.

476
00:29:20,969 --> 00:29:22,679
I could if I wanted to, but...

477
00:29:24,472 --> 00:29:25,640
I'm too tired.

478
00:29:27,434 --> 00:29:28,810
Who are you now?

479
00:29:30,311 --> 00:29:31,604
My name is Bruce Wayne.

480
00:29:33,106 --> 00:29:35,024
When was this we met before?

481
00:29:35,400 --> 00:29:36,776
Two years ago.

482
00:29:37,569 --> 00:29:38,862
An alley in the theater district.

483
00:29:39,028 --> 00:29:42,615
You killed my mother and father,
Thomas and Martha Wayne.

484
00:29:42,782 --> 00:29:44,367
I was there.

485
00:29:47,245 --> 00:29:48,705
Rings a bell.

486
00:29:50,915 --> 00:29:52,417
You looked right at me.

487
00:29:53,084 --> 00:29:54,461
I was busy that year.

488
00:29:58,423 --> 00:30:00,258
My parents were important people.

489
00:30:02,385 --> 00:30:04,596
It was a big deal in all the newspapers.

490
00:30:04,846 --> 00:30:07,557
I don't read the papers much.
Don't watch TV.

491
00:30:07,765 --> 00:30:09,392
It's always the same bad news.

492
00:30:12,645 --> 00:30:14,063
You really don't remember?

493
00:30:14,230 --> 00:30:17,192
Oh, hey, some of 'em stick with you.

494
00:30:17,609 --> 00:30:20,862
There was this mustached fella,
he was a big fat crybaby,

495
00:30:22,071 --> 00:30:24,574
comes back to me in my dreams
all the time,

496
00:30:25,617 --> 00:30:27,368
like he's important.

497
00:30:28,244 --> 00:30:30,872
I can't even recall his name.

498
00:30:31,539 --> 00:30:33,833
<i>Did I stab him? Toss him off a roof?</i>

499
00:30:35,376 --> 00:30:36,669
I don't know.

500
00:30:37,128 --> 00:30:39,631
My parents were in evening clothes.

501
00:30:40,757 --> 00:30:41,883
It was cold and wet.

502
00:30:47,138 --> 00:30:49,390
You grabbed my mother's pearl necklace,
it broke.

503
00:30:52,101 --> 00:30:53,394
Oh...

504
00:30:56,481 --> 00:30:57,982
Oh, yeah.

505
00:31:00,193 --> 00:31:02,195
And the beads went everywhere.

506
00:31:02,570 --> 00:31:04,280
<i>Coming back to me now.</i>

507
00:31:06,282 --> 00:31:11,120
Nice looking blonde lady,
silver fox type dude, and a kid.

508
00:31:13,623 --> 00:31:14,999
That was you?

509
00:31:16,292 --> 00:31:17,627
That was me.

510
00:31:19,254 --> 00:31:20,588
Who hired you?

511
00:31:20,755 --> 00:31:22,173
Maybe nobody did.

512
00:31:23,132 --> 00:31:24,676
Maybe I just saw some rich suckers.

513
00:31:25,677 --> 00:31:28,263
Somebody like that
walks into a dark alley,

514
00:31:28,471 --> 00:31:30,223
they deserved it
'cause they let it happen.

515
00:31:31,641 --> 00:31:33,268
That's the way of the world,
isn't it, son?

516
00:31:33,434 --> 00:31:34,519
Don't call me son.

517
00:31:34,686 --> 00:31:37,981
Why? If I did what you think I did,
then I made you what you are.

518
00:31:39,399 --> 00:31:40,817
Just like Gotham made me.

519
00:31:42,402 --> 00:31:45,321
<i>Just like the rich folks
like your parents made Gotham.</i>

520
00:31:47,824 --> 00:31:49,784
I might as well call you son.

521
00:31:51,244 --> 00:31:53,413
I can make you tell me who hired you.

522
00:31:55,290 --> 00:31:56,624
You think so?

523
00:31:56,791 --> 00:31:58,167
I could hurt you.

524
00:31:59,502 --> 00:32:00,962
I can shoot you in the knee.

525
00:32:03,131 --> 00:32:04,757
Or the stomach.

526
00:32:04,924 --> 00:32:07,343
But you can't make me
tell you a damn thing.

527
00:32:09,512 --> 00:32:11,931
Killer's code ain't much,
but it's what I've got.

528
00:32:14,517 --> 00:32:17,520
If I did what you say I did
and someone hired me to do it,

529
00:32:18,271 --> 00:32:19,814
you'll never know their name.

530
00:32:20,189 --> 00:32:23,526
<i>Not if you take me apart piece by piece.</i>

531
00:32:23,860 --> 00:32:25,528
You better believe that.

532
00:32:26,946 --> 00:32:29,032
Well, then I guess
there's nothing left to say.

533
00:32:29,240 --> 00:32:30,491
(COCKS GUN)

534
00:32:34,454 --> 00:32:36,039
Here's to you, son.

535
00:32:38,708 --> 00:32:40,710
You've been a long time coming.

536
00:32:42,170 --> 00:32:43,504
You want me to kill you?

537
00:32:45,340 --> 00:32:46,716
Why?

538
00:32:50,011 --> 00:32:52,472
Little rich kid like you
wouldn't understand.

539
00:32:54,223 --> 00:32:55,725
Try me.

540
00:32:58,978 --> 00:33:00,897
A man gets tired.

541
00:33:04,233 --> 00:33:06,986
Doing wrong and going unpunished.

542
00:33:08,655 --> 00:33:10,031
<i>Nothing happens.</i>

543
00:33:13,660 --> 00:33:16,996
You start to wonder if there is a God.

544
00:33:26,547 --> 00:33:27,757
Tighten your left hand grip.

545
00:33:29,509 --> 00:33:31,761
<i>Aim right here,</i>

546
00:33:32,887 --> 00:33:35,264
a little low. She'll kick.

547
00:33:42,188 --> 00:33:44,482
Come on. Pull the damn trigger.

548
00:33:47,110 --> 00:33:48,277
No.

549
00:33:48,444 --> 00:33:50,363
Don't lose your nerve now. Do it!

550
00:33:51,948 --> 00:33:53,616
Look at me.

551
00:33:56,369 --> 00:33:58,162
I'm a monster.

552
00:34:01,457 --> 00:34:02,875
You need to kill me.

553
00:34:05,628 --> 00:34:07,380
I wish you were a monster.

554
00:34:11,801 --> 00:34:13,428
But you're just a man.

555
00:34:23,312 --> 00:34:24,313
Bruce.

556
00:34:24,605 --> 00:34:26,315
- He's in there.
- (GUNSHOT)

557
00:34:50,840 --> 00:34:52,216
(PANTING)

558
00:34:54,552 --> 00:34:55,887
- MALE NURSE: Good luck, buddy.
- Huh.

559
00:34:56,179 --> 00:34:58,097
Hey. Hey.

560
00:34:59,307 --> 00:35:00,516
Hey!

561
00:35:00,683 --> 00:35:02,852
I think there's been a mistake.

562
00:35:20,536 --> 00:35:22,371
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

563
00:35:24,582 --> 00:35:26,501
- (WHISPERS) Just wait.
- Hey.

564
00:35:27,084 --> 00:35:28,211
Who's there?

565
00:35:33,841 --> 00:35:35,218
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

566
00:35:35,468 --> 00:35:37,720
- (GRUNTS)
- No. Remember me?

567
00:35:37,970 --> 00:35:39,806
I'm the man with the ice cream.

568
00:35:40,014 --> 00:35:42,141
(BREATHING HEAVILY) Oh, yeah.

569
00:35:42,308 --> 00:35:45,269
(CHUCKLES) Yeah.
You knocked me around pretty good.

570
00:35:46,354 --> 00:35:48,439
I guess that ice cream
must be delicious, huh?

571
00:35:48,606 --> 00:35:49,899
(CHUCKLES) It was pretty good.

572
00:35:51,943 --> 00:35:53,569
You look kind of uncomfortable.

573
00:35:56,364 --> 00:35:58,616
I have a sharp knife here.

574
00:35:59,742 --> 00:36:01,035
What say I help you out?

575
00:36:01,786 --> 00:36:03,120
HELZINGER: Help me out?

576
00:36:03,579 --> 00:36:06,415
You have to promise to be nice, okay?

577
00:36:06,791 --> 00:36:10,545
There's no ice cream in here,
so there's no reason to get mad. Okay?

578
00:36:10,878 --> 00:36:11,879
Promise?

579
00:36:12,046 --> 00:36:13,130
Okay.

580
00:36:19,136 --> 00:36:20,763
(GRUNTS AND CHUCKLES)

581
00:36:23,724 --> 00:36:25,601
<i>- There you go.
- Thank you.</i>

582
00:36:26,561 --> 00:36:27,770
COBBLEPOT: Oh, you're welcome.

583
00:36:31,315 --> 00:36:33,150
HUGO: <i>Bravo, Cobblepot.</i>

584
00:36:33,901 --> 00:36:35,111
Sir?

585
00:36:36,612 --> 00:36:40,491
This is an official certificate from
the Gotham Board of Health and Hygiene.

586
00:36:40,658 --> 00:36:44,912
It states that Oswald Cobblepot
has passed all mandated tests,

587
00:36:45,079 --> 00:36:49,667
and by the laws of Gotham City
is hereby declared

588
00:36:49,834 --> 00:36:51,127
sane.

589
00:36:55,673 --> 00:36:56,841
I'm sane?

590
00:36:57,008 --> 00:37:01,012
You're as sane and normal
as any other citizen.

591
00:37:01,554 --> 00:37:03,681
Ms. Peabody even.

592
00:37:04,640 --> 00:37:06,350
<i>Do you know what that means?</i>

593
00:37:07,226 --> 00:37:08,686
No more therapy?

594
00:37:08,853 --> 00:37:12,023
Oswald, you're a free man.

595
00:37:12,690 --> 00:37:13,900
I don't follow you.

596
00:37:14,066 --> 00:37:16,903
You are sane,
ergo there is no reason for you

597
00:37:17,069 --> 00:37:19,363
to be in a mental health institution.

598
00:37:19,530 --> 00:37:21,949
You are free to go.

599
00:37:22,366 --> 00:37:23,910
I'm fine right here.

600
00:37:24,076 --> 00:37:29,290
Oswald, Oswald, Oswald,
you are just feeling anxious about change.

601
00:37:29,457 --> 00:37:32,960
That is totally normal, to feel that way
upon release from care.

602
00:37:33,961 --> 00:37:36,964
Okay. I guess if it's normal...

603
00:37:37,340 --> 00:37:41,802
You are a sane, gentle, good man.

604
00:37:41,969 --> 00:37:44,597
And good things happen to good people.

605
00:37:45,389 --> 00:37:46,474
They do?

606
00:37:47,350 --> 00:37:49,393
I've never heard that before.

607
00:37:50,311 --> 00:37:52,980
A true thing. Trust me.

608
00:37:53,940 --> 00:37:56,651
Well, you've been right so far. (CHUCKLES)

609
00:37:57,485 --> 00:37:59,528
Thank you, Professor Strange-- Hugo...

610
00:37:59,779 --> 00:38:00,780
(CHUCKLING)

611
00:38:00,988 --> 00:38:04,867
...for being such a kind mentor
and friend.

612
00:38:05,660 --> 00:38:07,995
That's very touching, Oswald.

613
00:38:08,955 --> 00:38:10,706
<i>Thank you so much.</i>

614
00:38:10,873 --> 00:38:13,042
And now,
why don't you go back to your room

615
00:38:13,209 --> 00:38:15,378
and get your belongings together.

616
00:38:15,920 --> 00:38:17,380
Okay. (CHUCKLES)

617
00:38:22,677 --> 00:38:24,095
(CHUCKLES)

618
00:38:25,930 --> 00:38:27,890
- (BUZZER SOUNDS)
- (DOOR OPENS)

619
00:38:28,724 --> 00:38:31,060
Are you sure about that? Letting him go?

620
00:38:31,227 --> 00:38:32,937
Not really. He's an experiment.

621
00:38:33,104 --> 00:38:35,773
He's a notorious criminal.
There'll be an outcry.

622
00:38:35,940 --> 00:38:37,316
The outcry will pass.

623
00:38:37,483 --> 00:38:39,735
People are afraid of progress,
Ms. Peabody,

624
00:38:39,902 --> 00:38:42,113
and yet somehow we keep progressing.

625
00:38:42,279 --> 00:38:44,949
I hope you'll at least alert the police
he's been released.

626
00:38:45,116 --> 00:38:47,284
Enough input, Ms. Peabody.

627
00:38:47,451 --> 00:38:50,746
I have other reasons,
deeper plans for Cobblepot

628
00:38:50,913 --> 00:38:52,581
that you can't know about now.

629
00:38:52,748 --> 00:38:54,750
(INHALES DEEPLY) For your own safety.

630
00:38:55,251 --> 00:38:57,086
Deeper plans?

631
00:39:00,006 --> 00:39:03,175
Deeper than building semi-human creatures
in the basement?

632
00:39:04,385 --> 00:39:07,513
I'm sure I don't want to know,
thank you very much.

633
00:39:07,680 --> 00:39:09,432
On your head be it.

634
00:39:31,996 --> 00:39:34,790
There's a reason why
we might've missed Malone, okay?

635
00:39:34,957 --> 00:39:37,043
His record goes back
to nursery school on up.

636
00:39:37,209 --> 00:39:40,963
Assault, robbery, battery, couple of hits
for the mob. But this is way, way back.

637
00:39:41,130 --> 00:39:42,381
Last few years, nothing.

638
00:39:42,548 --> 00:39:44,967
That's why his name
never came up as a potential suspect.

639
00:39:45,134 --> 00:39:47,303
Oh, flying under the radar, I guess.
It happens.

640
00:39:47,470 --> 00:39:48,721
Guess we'll never know
if he really did it.

641
00:39:48,888 --> 00:39:51,640
Ah, the boy says he confessed.
That's good enough for me.

642
00:39:52,933 --> 00:39:54,977
Malone killed the Waynes.

643
00:39:55,144 --> 00:39:57,229
The question is,
who paid him to kill the Waynes?

644
00:39:57,396 --> 00:39:59,482
It's a question
I no longer care to ponder.

645
00:40:02,651 --> 00:40:04,445
Hey, Ed. How you doing?

646
00:40:04,612 --> 00:40:07,656
Oh, getting along just fine. Keeping busy.

647
00:40:08,491 --> 00:40:09,825
Any news on the Kringle front?

648
00:40:10,409 --> 00:40:13,370
Uh, no. Damn.
Sorry, I've been a little busy.

649
00:40:13,662 --> 00:40:15,247
I'll get into it, don't worry.

650
00:40:15,748 --> 00:40:17,249
Me, worry? (CHUCKLES)

651
00:40:17,917 --> 00:40:20,169
Yeah. I'll let you know
as soon as I know anything.

652
00:40:21,128 --> 00:40:23,881
- Detective Gordon, do you have a second?
- Uh, yeah.

653
00:40:25,966 --> 00:40:30,513
You'll let me know? I bet you will.

654
00:40:30,679 --> 00:40:34,350
Acting like you forgot all about
Kristen Kringle. Sure you forgot.

655
00:40:34,517 --> 00:40:36,685
- You're ready.
- Thanks, Detective.

656
00:40:36,852 --> 00:40:38,395
ED: <i>You suspect me somehow.
That must be it.</i>

657
00:40:39,313 --> 00:40:42,483
You're trying to lull me
into a false sense of security

658
00:40:42,650 --> 00:40:45,194
while the claws of your investigation
close around me, eh?

659
00:40:45,361 --> 00:40:46,737
Is that it, my little man?

660
00:40:46,904 --> 00:40:48,656
You take me to be a fool?

661
00:40:49,156 --> 00:40:51,867
<i>We'll see about your clever little plan,
Jim Gordon. We'll see.</i>

662
00:40:53,494 --> 00:40:56,080
I can make plans of my own.

663
00:40:59,416 --> 00:41:01,043
ALFRED: <i>Master Bruce.</i>

664
00:41:12,513 --> 00:41:14,765
BRUCE: <i>Alfred,
I have left home for a while</i>

665
00:41:14,974 --> 00:41:16,809
<i>to live on the streets with Selina.</i>

666
00:41:16,976 --> 00:41:20,563
<i>Please. Wait and listen before you react.</i>

667
00:41:20,729 --> 00:41:23,899
<i>You need not worry that I'm in danger,
or that I've lost my mind.</i>

668
00:41:25,734 --> 00:41:27,903
<i>I've thought long and hard
about this decision.</i>

669
00:41:28,070 --> 00:41:29,864
<i>And I know it's the right one.</i>

670
00:41:30,030 --> 00:41:32,700
<i>Malone's death made me realize
a couple of things.</i>

671
00:41:33,325 --> 00:41:37,746
<i>You can't kill murder.
You can't get revenge on evil.</i>

672
00:41:37,913 --> 00:41:41,250
<i>You can only begin to fight such things
by not doing them.</i>

673
00:41:41,417 --> 00:41:43,210
<i>And you can only fight them
where they live.</i>

674
00:41:43,377 --> 00:41:47,965
<i>Not just at Wayne Enterprises.
In the streets, in the slums,</i>

675
00:41:48,132 --> 00:41:49,800
<i>in the bad parts of town.</i>

676
00:41:50,634 --> 00:41:52,595
<i>So that's where I'm going.</i>

677
00:41:52,845 --> 00:41:55,264
He's lost his mind.

678
00:41:55,431 --> 00:41:58,058
BRUCE: <i>I'm not going to start
battling muggers or anything.</i>

679
00:41:58,225 --> 00:42:02,354
<i>But one day I am going to do something
to help the people of Gotham.</i>

680
00:42:02,521 --> 00:42:03,814
<i>I don't know what yet.</i>

681
00:42:05,065 --> 00:42:06,525
<i>But I will.</i>

682
00:42:06,692 --> 00:42:08,777
<i>Meantime, I need to learn stuff.</i>

683
00:42:08,944 --> 00:42:10,487
<i>Number one, I need to learn how to live</i>

684
00:42:10,654 --> 00:42:12,698
<i>in the same world
other people have to live in.</i>

685
00:42:12,990 --> 00:42:16,827
<i>Selina is giving me a place to sleep
and will show me the ropes,</i>

686
00:42:18,454 --> 00:42:20,623
<i>so like I say, there's no need to worry.</i>

687
00:42:21,624 --> 00:42:25,252
<i>I'll be in touch soon,
and I'll come home eventually.</i>

688
00:42:26,212 --> 00:42:31,091
<i>Please, Alfred, trust me,
and honor my wishes.</i>

689
00:42:31,258 --> 00:42:33,219
<i>Don't try to bring me back.</i>

690
00:42:33,385 --> 00:42:35,804
<i>I need to do this.</i>

691
00:42:35,971 --> 00:42:39,058
<i>Sincerely, your good friend,</i>

692
00:42:40,309 --> 00:42:41,310
<i>Bruce.</i>

693
00:44:01,890 --> 00:44:02,891
English - SDH

